{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}} {{Infobox religious building |image= Royal Mosque and terraces of houses, Qazvin by Eugène Flandin.jpg |caption= 1840 |building_name= Al-Nabi Mosque of [[Qazvin (city)|Qazvīn]] |location= [[Qazvīn]], Iran |geo= |religious_affiliation= [[Shia Islam]] |province= [[Qazvīn Province]] |municipality= [[Qazvīn County]] |website= |architect= |architecture_type= Mosque |architecture_style= | interior_area =~{{convert|14,000|m2|abbr=on}} |year_completed=16th century |construction_cost= |capacity= |dome_quantity= |dome_height_outer= |dome_dia_outer= |minaret_quantity= |minaret_height= }}
The '''al-Nabi Mosque''' ({{lang-fa|مسجد النبی قزوین}} – ''Masjed al-Nabi'', also known as: {{lang-fa|مسجد سلطانى}} – '''Masjed-e Soltani''') is a famous mosque in [[Qazvīn]]. The mosque has an area of about 14,000 m²,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.mehrnews.com/news/50344/Al-Nabi-Mosque-in-Qazvin|title=Al-Nabi Mosque in Qazvin|date=2012-03-05|work=Mehr News Agency|access-date=2018-02-02|language=en}}</ref> and bears inscriptions indicating that [[Fath Ali Shah]] of the [[Qajar dynasty]] was the founder of the mosque. Other sources however indicate that the mosque has been in existence since the [[Safavid]] period. It is now believed that the architect of the structure was ''Ustad Mirza Shirazi'' with the date of construction being 1787. This glorious mosque also known as Masjed Nabi, Masjed Soltani or Masjed Shah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://persiaport.com/en/attractions/al-nabi-mosque-of-qazvin|title=Al-Nabi Mosque of Qazvin|last=PersiaPort|website=PersiaPort|language=en|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref>
==Specifications== Its double layered dome measures 15m in inner-diameter, with the top of the inner layer positioned at 20.83m above ground level, while the external apex is 23.25m high.
There was formerly an elevated [[minaret]] flanking the dome, of which the French explorer [[Madame Jane Dieulafoy]] had written. The mosque has four [[iwan]]s in its courtyard.
The portal contains an inscription in [[nastaliq]] calligraphy dated 1787 CE. Similar to [[Jame' Atiq Mosque of Qazvin|Qazvin's Masjed e Jame (Congregation Mosque)]], this mosque has a [[shabestan]] that is now used as a library.
==See also== * [[List of Mosques in Iran]] * [[Iranian architecture]] * [[Islamic architecture]] [[Image:Masjed-alnabi-qazvin.jpg|thumb|right|Entrance of Masjed al-Nabi, Qazvin, Iran.]]
