{{DISPLAYTITLE:Aphrodite (''Hercules: The Legendary Journeys'' and ''Xena: Warrior Princess'')}}
{{Infobox character | name = Aphrodite | color = #A9A9A9 | image = | first = The Apple | last = Many Happy Returns | creator = [[Robert Tapert]] | occupation = Goddess Of Love | species = [[Deity|God]], occasionally human | portrayer = [[Alexandra Tydings]] | lbl21 = Affiliation | data21 = [[Xena]], [[Gabrielle (Xena)|Gabrielle]], [[Ares (Hercules: The Legendary Journeys and Xena: Warrior Princess)|Ares]] }}
'''Aphrodite''' is a [[fictional character]] played by [[Alexandra Tydings]] in ''[[Xena: Warrior Princess]]'' and ''[[Hercules: The Legendary Journeys]]''.
==Overview== [[Aphrodite]] is the [[Goddess]] of [[Romance (love)|Love]] on both ''Xena'' and ''Hercules''. Aphrodite inspires [[love]] and [[lust|passionate desire]] in humankind while her brother [[Ares (Hercules: The Legendary Journeys and Xena: Warrior Princess)|Ares]], her [[antithesis]], promotes [[war]]fare and conflict. Despite this conflict of values, Ares and Aphrodite are siblings and allies. Aphrodite is portrayed as a modern-day [[Greek Goddess]], with somewhat of a [[dumb blonde]] and usually vain persona. She is essentially good-natured and helpful; she is close friends with Gabrielle because of that. Nearly all of Aphrodite's attire resembles [[lingerie]], and she is nearly always barefoot. She romances [[Hephaestus]], but unlike the myths, their relationship is essentially a happy one.
==Character development== As in the myth of her birth, Aphrodite first appears [[Aphrodite#Birth.2C rising from the sea|rising out of the sea in a giant seashell]]. As a joke, she then uses the seashell to go [[windsurfing]].
Before her marriage to Hephaestus she is portrayed as being a bit promiscuous; she steals a boyfriend away from Hera and because of that Hera places a curse on her son [[Cupid]].<ref name="greeneyed">{{cite episode|title=The Green-Eyed Monster|series=Hercules: The Legendary Journeys|serieslink=Hercules: The Legendary Journeys|airdate=1996-11-11}}</ref> Cupid falls in love with a girl named [[Eros and Psyche|Psyche]], who is said to be more beautiful than Aphrodite, which makes her extremely jealous. Out of jealousy, Aphrodite tries to shoot a love arrow at Psyche, but Cupid tries to stop her.<ref name="greeneyed"/> This only makes things worse when [[Hercules]] is accidentally hit and falls in love with Psyche. Thanks to Hera's curse, Cupid literally turns into a green-eyed monster with jealousy at the thought of losing Psyche. The curse is eventually lifted when the truth comes, after he confesses his love for Psyche and she marries him. Aphrodite gives Psyche [[Ambrosia]] to make her a [[goddess]] to make amends, since she is the one who started the mess. Although she soon realizes she is now a mother-in-law, which does not make her very happy.<ref name="greeneyed"/> She becomes a grandmother later on when Psyche and Cupid have a son, Bliss.<ref name="comedy">{{cite episode|title=A Comedy of Eros|series=Xena: Warrior Princess|serieslink=Xena: Warrior Princess|airdate=1997-05-12}}</ref>
On ''Hercules'', Aphrodite is usually the comic relief or the viewers' window into the politics of [[Mount Olympus]]. Though she is originally introduced as a scheming goddess, devious and almost as uncaring as Ares, she quickly evolves into a more benevolent fun-loving character, though still prone to mood-swings. She is also the only member of his Olympian family Hercules seems to have any sort of close relationship with (in one episode he refers to her as his favorite little sister, and is somewhat close to her son Cupid who refers to him as "Uncle Herc"), despite the trouble he seems to cause him.
Aphrodite determines to break up a royal family marriage that will end a war, only because the newly allied kingdoms plan to destroy her temples. As her son Cupid explains to Gabrielle, "When the Goddess of Love decides to do something petty and spiteful, she can be a tad difficult to reason with."<ref name="bell tolls">{{cite episode|title=For Him the Bell Tolls|series=Xena: Warrior Princess|serieslink=Xena: Warrior Princess|airdate=1997-02-24}}</ref> She later develops a friendship with Gabrielle and tries to save her during the [[Wiktionary:massacre|massacre]] of the Olympian Gods.
Aphrodite becomes one of the survivors of the Twilight of the Olympian Gods, organized by Xena when the gods, under [[Athena]]'s flag, join together to kill [[Eve (Xena)|Eve]].<ref name="Motherhood">{{cite episode|title=Motherhood|series=Xena: Warrior Princess|serieslink=Xena: Warrior Princess|airdate=2000-05-15}}</ref> Aphrodite remains unconvinced that Eve will willingly destroy the gods, to the point where she sneaks Xena and Gabrielle into Olympus itself. After the Twilight of the Gods, Aphrodite becomes mentally unbalanced due to Ares losing his powers; Love must be balanced by War.<ref name="god you know">{{cite episode|title=The God You Know|series=Xena: Warrior Princess|serieslink=Xena: Warrior Princess|airdate=2001-01-29}}</ref> Her powers are stolen by [[Caligula]], whom Xena tricks into killing himself.<ref name="god you know"/> This makes matters worse, since love is now gone from the world altogether. Xena restores the powers of both Aphrodite and Ares using [[Golden apple#Norse mythology|golden apples]] she stole from the [[List of Hercules and Xena characters#Norse Gods|Norse Gods]], thereby restoring balance to the universe.<ref name="you are there">{{cite episode|title=You Are There|series=Xena: Warrior Princess|serieslink=Xena: Warrior Princess|airdate=2001-02-05}}</ref>
