{{italic title}} {{Infobox book | name = Anne of Green Gables | image = Penguins Stopped Play.jpg| caption = | alt = | author = [[Harry Thompson]] | title_orig = | working_title = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | series = | subject = Cricket, travel | genre = [[Sports journalism|Sports literature]] | publisher = [[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]] | pub_date = 2006 | pages = 256 ''(first edition)'' | awards = | isbn = 978-0719563454 | oclc = | congress = | preceded_by = This Thing of Darkness | followed_by = | wikisource = }} '''''Penguins Stopped Play: Eleven Village Cricketers Take on the World''''' is a 2006 [[semi-autobiographical novel]] by the English writer and producer [[Harry Thompson]]. It describes the author's experiences forming and travelling with the Captain Scott XI, an English amateur [[cricket]] team, around Britain and abroad.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jun/17/featuresreviews.guardianreview8|title=Over and out|author=[[Tim de Lisle]]|date=16 June 2006|accessdate=2 January 2017|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3652334/Eleven-village-cricketers-take-on-the-world.html|title=Eleven village cricketers take on the world|author=Tom Fort|work=[[Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=2 January 2017}}</ref> It was published a year after the author's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/4417656.stm|title=Have I Got News For You man dies|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=2 January 2017}}</ref>
In 2011 the book was adapted for a series of broadcasts on ''[[Book of the Week]]'', a weekly programme on [[BBC Radio 4]], read by the cricketer [[Nicholas Boulton (cricketer)|Nicholas Boulton]].<ref>{{cite new|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00lnn3r|title=Penguins Stopped Play - BBC Radio 4 Extra|work=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2 January 2017}}</ref>
