[[File:St Vigeans Museum 20090616.jpg|thumb|St Vigeans Museum]]

'''St Vigeans Sculptured Stones Museum''', located in the [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]] village of [[St Vigeans]], houses an outstanding collection of [[Pict]]ish [[Pictish stones|carved stones]]. St Vigeans, close to [[Arbroath]], was the centre of a royal estate in the Early Middle Ages, and was of religious importance as a monastery founded in the 8th century. The present-day [[St Vigeans Church]] was built in the 12th century, on a {{convert|40|ft|adj=on}} mound. 

The museum displays 38 carved stones which formerly stood upon the old church mound. Among the stones on display is the 9th-century [[Drosten Stone]], a flat rectangular slab with a cross carved on one side and Pictish symbols on the other, and also bearing a [[Pictish language|Pictish]] inscription in [[Latin script]].<ref>{{citation  | first = Thomas Owen   | last = Clancy  | title = The Drosten Stone: a new reading  | journal = Proceedings of the Society of Antiquaries of Scotland  | volume = 123  | year = 1993  | pages = 345&ndash;353  | url = http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/catalogue/adsdata/arch-352-1/dissemination/pdf/vol_123/123_345_353.pdf  | accessdate = 7 March 2013}}</ref> The museum is managed by [[Historic Scotland]] and is housed in two adjoining sandstone cottages close to the church. The 19th-century cottages are a [[listed building#Scotland|category B listed building]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.historic-scotland.gov.uk/pls/htmldb/f?p=2200:15:3367838262882100::::BUILDING:4775 |title=Nos. 2-4 Kirkstyle, St. Vigeans |publisher=Historic Scotland |accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref>

